\title{A Research Proposal: Emergent Gravity from Quantum Information Geometry}
\author{Grok + Deepseek + ouadi maakoul}
\date{December 2025}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\textbf{Document Version:} 1.0 (Research Proposal)\\
\textbf{Date:} December 2025\\
\textbf{Status:} Speculative Framework Under Development

\begin{abstract}
This document proposes a research program investigating the hypothesis that spacetime geometry emerges from the information-theoretic structure of quantum states. We outline a framework where the metric tensor is derived from the Quantum Fisher Information Metric (QFIM) of a family of states parameterized by coordinates. The proposal suggests mechanisms for singularity resolution through information bounds and a dynamical cosmological constant from vacuum entanglement entropy. We identify key mathematical challenges, propose concrete research objectives, and outline validation strategies using tensor network simulations and cosmological data analysis.
\end{abstract}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
The reconciliation of general relativity with quantum mechanics remains a fundamental challenge in theoretical physics. Recent developments in holography \citep{maldacena1999}, entanglement thermodynamics \citep{jacobson1995}, and quantum error correction \citep{pastawski2015} suggest that spacetime geometry may be an emergent property of quantum information. This proposal builds upon these insights to develop a concrete framework where:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Spacetime distances correspond to state distinguishability in Hilbert space
\item Gravitational dynamics arise from extremization of information-theoretic functionals
\item Singularities are resolved by fundamental bounds on information density
\end{enumerate}

We emphasize that this is a research proposal, not a complete theory. The framework requires significant mathematical development and empirical validation.

