\subsection{Observational Tests}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Black Hole Shadows: Compare predictions with Event Horizon Telescope observations
\item Gravitational Wave Astronomy: Search for post-merger echoes from Planck cores
\item Cosmological Surveys: Test evolving \(\Lambda(a)\) with DESI, Euclid, and Roman data. As of December 2025, the Hubble tension remains robust (>5\(\sigma\)): early-universe (CMB/Planck/ACT) ~67-68 km/s/Mpc; local (SH0ES/JWST/lensing) ~73-74 km/s/Mpc, motivating dynamic \(\Lambda\) models.
\item Laboratory Tests: Propose tabletop experiments for short-distance gravity modifications
\end{enumerate}

\section{Required Resources}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Computational:} Access to HPC clusters for tensor network simulations (e.g., TeNPy/ITensor libraries); ~100,000 core-hours annually (~\$15,000/year)
\item \textbf{Personnel:} 2-3 postdoctoral researchers (expertise in quantum information, holography, numerical methods) + principal investigator (~\$300,000 over 3 years)
\item \textbf{Conference Travel:} 3 conferences/year × 2 people (~\$15,000/year)
\item \textbf{Publication Fees:} Open access (~\$5,000)
\item \textbf{Total Estimated 3-Year Budget:} ~\$395,000 (details available upon request)
\end{itemize}

\section*{Ethics and Open Science}
\begin{itemize}
\item All code will be open-source (MIT license) on GitHub
\item Simulation data and results deposited in Zenodo
\item Preprints on arXiv prior to journal submission
\item Regular progress updates via research blog or public repository
\item Commitment to reproducible research and inclusive collaboration
\end{itemize}

\section{Open Challenges and Risks}

\subsection{Major Technical Challenges}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Mathematical Rigor: The pullback construction requires careful treatment of diffeomorphism invariance and gauge freedom in parameter space
\item Non-Perturbative Treatment: The framework may require non-perturbative methods beyond current computational capabilities
\item Matter Incorporation: Coupling to Standard Model fields is non-trivial and may require additional principles
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Potential Falsification Scenarios}
The proposal could be falsified by:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Mathematical Inconsistency: Discovery of unavoidable contradictions in the framework
\item Empirical Disproof: Observations contradicting key predictions (e.g., no Planck core signatures in black hole mergers)
\item Theoretical Redundancy: Demonstration that the framework is equivalent to existing approaches without new insights
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Alternative Interpretations}
We acknowledge that:
\begin{enumerate}
\item The proposed emergence mechanism may represent a duality rather than fundamental emergence
\item Information bounds might be consequences rather than causes of quantum gravity
\item The framework may need incorporation into broader approaches like string theory or loop quantum gravity
\end{enumerate}

\section{Conclusion and Future Directions}
This proposal outlines a research program to develop a framework where spacetime geometry emerges from quantum information. The key innovations are:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Systematic Approach: Using QFIM pullback to derive geometry
\item Dynamical Principle: Action combining geometric and informational terms
\item Singularity Resolution: Through fundamental information bounds
\end{enumerate}

Immediate Next Steps:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Complete the SYK-JT gravity example calculation
\item Develop numerical tools for QFIM computation in tensor networks
\item Formulate precise mathematical statement of the Fisher bound conjecture
\end{enumerate}

Long-Term Vision: If successful, this research could provide:
\begin{itemize}
\item A first-principles derivation of gravity from quantum information
\item Resolution of spacetime singularities
\item New insights into dark energy and cosmic acceleration
\item Connections between quantum gravity and quantum computing
\end{itemize}

